Question_Text: Over the past 14 days, how consistent is your wake time (± minutes), and what is the pattern when it breaks?
What is the earliest time you can realistically be in bed on weekdays without resentment? What blocks it?
What is your caffeine/nicotine signature (timing + dose)? What symptom does it temporarily solve?
When do you feel your first real drop in energy each day? What are you doing right before it?
Under pressure, do you hold your breath, go shallow, or speed up? What trigger reliably flips it?
Where does stress land first (jaw/chest/gut/neck)? What are you usually thinking in that exact moment?
Which sensory inputs (noise, lighting, texture, crowds) spike your irritability fastest—and what do you do next?
How often do you override hunger/thirst/toilet/rest signals for ‘just one more task’? What does it cost you later?
What is your shutdown tell (zoning out, blank mind, heavy limbs)? How early can you catch it?
When was the last time your body moved hard enough to change your mood within 20 minutes? What stopped you recently?
Which decision are you deferring because it will create conflict, loss, or identity discomfort?
How many open loops are you carrying right now (tasks, messages, promises)? Which 3 are draining 80% of your RAM?
Where do you demand certainty that reality cannot provide—and how do you punish yourself for not having it?
What fear are you disguising as logic this week?
Before high-stakes meetings, what does your mind assume others will discover about you?
What scenario does your brain replay when idle or waiting—and what emotion is it trying to avoid?
Which metric controls your mood more than it should—and what does that metric symbolize to you?
What does your mind do when forced to wait (traffic, loading, delays): rage, scroll, plan, numb out, or rehearse?
What standard are you using that no human could meet—yet you treat it as ‘baseline’?
Where does your work expand because stopping would force you to feel something?
How many times per hour do you switch contexts? What is the hidden trigger for each switch?
When you receive unexpected bad news, what is your first internal sentence?
What is the smallest ‘deep work’ block you can protect daily without negotiation—and what will you delete to fund it?
If your company disappeared tomorrow, what would be the first identity sentence you’d say about yourself?
What criticism hits you deepest—and what does it ‘confirm’ about you?
What do you believe you must achieve to finally feel ‘enough’?
What emotion shows up when you cannot control outcomes (grief, anger, fear, shame)?
If you stopped trying to ‘win’ at work, what emotion would you be forced to feel?
Contraindications: Avoid if client is currently in acute depressive episode.

Question_Text: What do you hide behind competence (need, sadness, fear, longing)?
Where are you betraying your own values to keep momentum—and how do you justify it?
What story do you tell yourself to make rest feel ‘unsafe’ or ‘undeserved’?
What do you call ‘productivity’ that is actually avoidance?
What important thing are you ‘almost starting’ all the time?
Which recovery input are you under-investing in by 30%+ (sleep, movement, connection)?
What commitment should be downgraded, delegated, or deleted this week?
Does spending money make you feel safe, powerful, or guilty—and what belief drives that reaction?
What are you buying with late-night work (certainty, relief, control, worth)? Did you get it?
In crisis mode, what do you neglect first: sleep, food, relationships, or honesty? Why?
What system would remove the most repeated effort from your week if you built it once?
Where do you feel most alone in your life right now—even when surrounded by people?
What boundary do you set too late (or not at all) because you fear consequences?
Do you trust people until they give you a reason not to, or mistrust until proven? What did that strategy cost you?
Who reliably calms your nervous system—and why aren’t they scheduled into your week?
Under conflict, what is your default move (pursue/withdraw/freeze/fawn/attack), and what is it protecting?
After a rupture, do you repair quickly or let distance calcify? What story justifies your choice?
Where are you carrying emotional labor that should be shared—and what prevents you from delegating it?
Which relationship has become purely transactional—and what would it take to make it human again?
Name 3 past situations where you were under pressure and still performed well. What did you do that worked?
What is one recovery behavior that has reliably worked for you before—and why did you stop doing it?
What would it look like to be 10% less heroic and 10% more sustainable this month?
